history.content: 110 + 113 + 170 should be pretty similar. 104 should be harder than 110 or 113 (depending on who’s teaching each one), and 170 is similar intensity to 70. I’m not sure how to compare 188 but I think it would have a similar difficulty to 110 overall.

children.subject: I took the all three in combination along with EE16B last semester and it is definitely doable. I think if you've already taken Math 104, Math 110 and 113 will be much easier. I'm pretty sure you know that upper div math classes have much less required work but are much more intensive in terms of difficulty. I heard Olga Holtz is teaching 110 though so I would take that into account because her classes may as well be considered "honors" in comparison to other professors. CS 170 is a lot more difficult than 70 and with slightly more workload in my opinion. I do think I struggled in the beginning of CS 170 as there is a jump from lower division to upper division courses. With lower division courses, as long as you put in the work, you can succeed but upper division courses require some level of "ingenuity" that hard work simply can't reward, but that may have been just me.

history.content:
Hi, intended CS + Math double major, declaring this semester. With the current state of enrollment it seems unlikely I'll be able to get into any upper div CS classes I'd like to take besides 170 without the priority of being declared. So I figured I'd take more math requirements (they're significantly easier to get into).

Was wondering if anyone had any advice on taking these three classes in combination. For reference, I'm taking CS 188, CS 70, and Math 104 in combination this semester and haven't had problems.
